      "stagesDesc": "Each stage represents one LLM pass. Click + to add stages. Expand a stage to configure its provider, model, and prompt. Use the wand icon to have the AI rewrite the prompt, or save/load prompts as reusable templates with the bookmark buttons. You can disable stages without deleting them.",
      "runTitle": "Running the pipeline",
      "runDesc": "After pasting your text in the center panel and clicking 'Stage Content', press 'Begin Pipeline'. Each stage runs sequentially per chunk, and you'll see tokens stream in real time. The judge runs automatically after all stages complete.",
      "editTitle": "Editing the result",
      "editDesc": "The 'Candidate Translation' box is fully editable. Make manual corrections, then click 'Re-Evaluate Drafts' in the audit panel to get an updated quality judgment on your edits.",
      "tipTitle": "Pro tip: mix providers",
      "tipDesc": "Use different models for different stages. A fast model (Gemini Flash, DeepSeek) works well for initial drafts, while a stronger model (GPT-4o, Claude Sonnet) excels at refinement and judging. Ollama models are ideal for offline work or sensitive content."
    },
    "features": {
      "title": "Advanced Features",
      "intro": "This section covers the most recent additions to Glossa.",
      "configDrawerTitle": "Configuration Panel (3 tabs)",
      "configDrawerDesc": "The configuration panel opens via the gear icon in the header. It is organised into three tabs: Stages (model, provider and prompt for each translation stage), Audit (shared audit model, Judge Prompt, and Coherence Prompt), Registry (glossary term management). The panel is a side drawer that overlays without obstructing the document text.",
      "documentToolsTitle": "Refined document reader",
      "documentToolsDesc": "The source and translation editors now use a collapsible toolbar so the chrome disappears when you just want to read or edit raw text. Candidate translations can be validated and locked with the green check button, while the full output of any stage opens in a dedicated modal when you click its status badge in the chunk row.",
      "templatesTitle": "Prompt Templates",
      "templatesDesc": "Every prompt textarea — in each stage and in both prompts of the Audit section — has save and load template buttons. Click the bookmark (+) to save the current prompt under a name; click the open book to browse and load saved templates (with search). Templates are separated by context: stage templates do not appear in the Audit section and vice versa. Saving a template with an existing name updates it automatically.",
      "refineTitle": "Refine Prompt",
      "refineDesc": "The wand icon next to each prompt sends the current text to the AI using the currently selected provider and model. Translation stages use their own stage model; the Audit section uses the shared audit model to refine both the Judge Prompt and the Coherence Prompt. The result appears immediately in the textarea — edit it freely or press Ctrl+Z to undo.",
      "tokenTitle": "Token Count and Estimated Cost",
      "tokenDesc": "The header displays in real time the total tokens consumed and the estimated cost for the current session, based on official pricing for each provider. Tokens are tracked separately for each stage and for the judge. The counter updates after each completed chunk.",
      "sandboxTitle": "Sandbox and Document Mode",
      "sandboxDesc": "The Sandbox button in the header toggles between two working modes. Sandbox is ideal for quick tests, model comparisons, and short single-text translations without chunks. Document mode activates the chunk reader, navigable index, insights panel, and advanced segmentation controls — suited for longer texts translated in multiple independent chunks.",
      "exportTitle": "Export",
      "exportDesc": "Export buttons are located in the Summary section of the header (visible when there are completed chunks). You can export the translated text as .txt, a review report as .html, or a .docx. If the document is Markdown-aware, a bilingual .md export is also available with original text, translation, audit quality, and flagged issues per chunk.",
      "segmentationTitle": "Document Segmentation",
      "segmentationDesc": "When importing a file, the segmentation panel lets you fine-tune how the document is split into chunks. 'Words per chunk' sets the desired chunk size — Glossa computes the number of chunks from the total word count automatically. 'Min words per chunk' prevents very short chunks (e.g. a lone heading) from being processed in isolation: chunks below this threshold are merged with the next one. 'Max words per chunk' splits oversized chunks that exceed the limit. 'Merge headings with next chunk' detects Markdown heading lines (# … ######) and attaches them to the following paragraph so a heading is never translated in isolation.",
      "chunkActionsTitle": "Chunk Actions (Index panel)",
      "chunkActionsDesc": "In the Index tab of the Insights panel, each unprocessed chunk shows two inline action buttons. Split divides the chunk into two halves at its midpoint — useful when a chunk is too long or contains two distinct topics. Both halves are reset to unprocessed and can be translated independently. Merge next fuses the chunk with the one immediately below it into a single larger chunk — useful when two consecutive chunks are too short or belong to the same narrative unit. Merge is only available when neither chunk has been processed yet. Both operations are instant and reversible: re-import or re-segment the document if needed.",
      "rollingContextTitle": "Rolling Context",
      "rollingContextDesc": "When 'Rolling context' is enabled, the last ~300 words of the previous chunk's translation are silently passed to the next chunk's prompt as background context. The model uses this tail to maintain terminological and stylistic coherence across chunk boundaries without re-reading the entire previous chunk. It is enabled by default. Rolling context has no effect on the first chunk or on single-chunk documents."
    },
    "streaming": {
      "title": "Real-time Streaming",
      "p1": "All translation stages stream tokens in real time. As the LLM generates text, you see it appear word by word in the stage output box. This gives immediate feedback and lets you spot issues early without waiting for the full response.",
      "p2": "Streaming works across all five providers: Gemini, OpenAI, Anthropic, DeepSeek, and Ollama. The connection uses Server-Sent Events (SSE) on the backend, with Tauri events relaying tokens to the frontend.",
      "p3": "The AI Judge does not stream — it returns structured JSON (quality rating + issues) which is displayed once complete. If a stage fails during streaming, the system retries automatically with exponential backoff (up to 3 attempts)."
    },
    "audit": {
      "title": "Audit & Quality Control",
      "intro": "The right panel shows audit results from the AI Judge. After the pipeline completes, each chunk receives a semantic quality label. The judge produces four categories of issues:",
      "glossaryIssue": "The translation deviates from the terms defined in your Keyword Registry.",
      "accuracyIssue": "The meaning of the source text is not faithfully rendered in the translation.",
      "fluencyIssue": "The translation reads unnaturally or has awkward phrasing in the target language.",
      "grammarIssue": "Grammatical errors, incorrect conjugations, or syntactic issues in the output.",
      "reeval": "After manually editing the candidate translation, click 'Re-Evaluate Drafts' to run the judge again on your updated text. This lets you iterate until the quality judgment meets your standards without re-running the entire pipeline.",
      "issuesNav": "Issue cards in the audit open the relevant chunk in the document reader. Jumping to the exact text fragment is still heuristic until the judge returns structured offsets."
    },
    "projects": {
      "title": "Projects & Files",
      "intro": "Glossa saves your work in local SQLite — all data stays on your machine.",
      "createTitle": "Create a project",
      "createDesc": "You can start working immediately in an unsaved draft. When you want to persist it, click Save in the header: on the first save a lightweight dialog asks for the project name. The Projects panel remains useful for opening, explicitly creating, or deleting saved projects.",
      "saveTitle": "Save your work",
      "saveDesc": "Click the save icon at any time to persist the current state. When you reopen a project, the full pipeline config, stages, glossary, and translations are restored exactly as you left them.",
      "importExportTitle": "Import and export",
      "importExportDesc": "Use the upload icon to import a .txt or .md file as source text. Export buttons appear in the Summary section of the header when chunks are completed: export as .txt for the translated text, or as .md for a bilingual Markdown document with original text, translation, audit quality, and issues."
    },
    "providers": {
      "title": "LLM Providers",
      "intro": "Glossa supports five providers. Each stage and the judge can use a different provider and model. Configure API keys in Settings.",
      "provider": "Provider",
      "models": "Models",
      "notes": "Notes",
      "geminiNote": "Google's models. Fast and cost-effective.",
      "openaiNote": "GPT-4o family. Strong general-purpose translation.",
      "anthropicNote": "Claude models. Excellent for nuanced, literary text.",
      "deepseekNote": "Chinese AI lab. Competitive pricing, good multilingual support.",
      "ollamaModels": "Any installed model",
      "ollamaNote": "Runs locally. No API key. Fully private.",
      "security": "API keys are stored in your operating system's keychain (GNOME Keyring on Linux, Keychain on macOS, Credential Manager on Windows). They are never written to disk in plain text and never sent anywhere except to the provider's API endpoint."
    },
    "ollama": {
      "title": "Using Ollama",
      "intro": "Ollama lets you run open-source LLMs entirely on your machine. No API key needed, no data leaves your computer. This is ideal for sensitive documents or offline work.",
      "installTitle": "Install Ollama",
      "installDesc": "Download from ollama.com or use the install script:",
      "pullTitle": "Pull a model",
      "pullDesc": "Download the model you want to use. Popular choices for translation:",
      "serveTitle": "Start the server",
      "serveDesc": "Ollama must be running in the background. If it's not already:",
      "useTitle": "Use in Glossa",
      "useDesc": "Open Settings — the Ollama section shows connection status and available models. Select 'ollama' as the provider in any stage or the judge, then pick a model from the dropdown.",
      "recommendedTitle": "Recommended models for translation",
      "recommendedDesc": "For general translation: llama3.2 (8B), mistral (7B), or gemma2 (9B). For higher quality on a capable machine: llama3.1:70b or mixtral:8x7b. Smaller models (< 3B parameters) may produce lower quality translations."
    },
    "glossary": {
      "title": "Library: Dictionaries & Prompt Templates",
      "intro": "Glossa includes a global library of reusable dictionaries shared across projects. Each dictionary holds source→translation pairs with optional notes. You can assign a dictionary to a project, edit its entries, and bulk-import terms from CSV files.",
      "libraryTitle": "Global dictionaries",
      "libraryDesc": "Click the Library icon in the header (General cluster, far right) to open the panel. In the Dictionaries tab you can create new dictionaries, rename them (double-click), duplicate them (Fork), delete them, and import terms from CSV/TSV. Expand a dictionary to edit its entries inline.",
      "csvTitle": "Import from CSV/TSV",
      "csvDesc": "Click the Upload button next to any dictionary to import terms from a file. A wizard shows a preview of the first 5 rows and asks for a strategy: «Add/update» adds new terms without touching existing ones; «Replace all» deletes all entries and reimports from the file. Recognised headers: term/source/from for the source term, translation/target/to for the translation (case-insensitive). The notes column is optional.",
      "projectTitle": "Per-project dictionary",
      "projectDesc": "In the Project Configuration panel (gear icon → Registry tab) you'll find a dropdown to select the dictionary assigned to the project. Edit entries inline in the editor: changes affect the shared dictionary and are persisted with the Save button that appears as soon as you make a change. The same dictionary can be assigned to multiple projects: entries are shared, and updating an entry from one project updates it for all.",
      "highlightTitle": "Term highlighting",
      "highlightDesc": "In the document reader and Sandbox mode, the Highlight terms button (brush icon) in the chunk action bar activates a visual overlay. In the source text, terms present in the dictionary are underlined in blue. In the candidate translation, correctly translated terms appear with a green background; source terms found but with a missing or different translation appear with a red background. Hover over a highlighted term to see the expected translation and any notes.",
      "auditTitle": "Audit and glossary",
      "auditDesc": "The AI Judge specifically checks adherence to the assigned dictionary. If the translation uses a different term than what's defined in the registry, it will flag a 'glossary' issue with severity and a suggested fix. This is especially valuable for technical, legal, or academic texts where terminology must be consistent.",
      "templatesTitle": "Prompt Templates",
      "templatesDesc": "In the Library panel (Prompt Templates tab) you manage the global collection of reusable templates. Create a template by specifying a name, context (Stage or Audit), and prompt text. Use the wand button in the creation form to have the AI rewrite the prompt: select the provider and model from the inline dropdowns and click the wand. Saved templates are available in all translation stages and in both prompts of the Audit section via the bookmark buttons (save/load)."
    },
